Inflation in Europe has erupted on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was more important than the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, indicated the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg.
The official estimates indicated only 3 percent, reported Bloomberg.
Contrary to the US, British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) did not lower the direct interest rate by saying that the decline in interest, with the growth of raw materials prices and the decline in unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to maintain the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is the Catch 22 for the ECB: “It is necessary to deter inflation so that it will no longer have to intervene on this issue later.
In Germany, the rate of inflation of 3.3 percent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area took off because of the rapid increase in food and energy prices.
Cereal market rates have increased by 88 percent and soya prices have also reached their highest value since 1973.
Food oil and milk products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and last month, a barrel of black gold cost almost $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will grow from 2.1, this year to 2.5 percent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 per cent, however, within 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 per cent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to decrease the steering rate twice in 2008.
