Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by nearly twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the trade triangle of Buddhaörs have maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year, unlike this year's VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Dayly Economy)
This year, in the trade triangle of Budaörs, the usual Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a significantly higher value increase than a thousand forints appeared in all hypermarkets.
The prices, \"which had already flowed\" in the large food stores last December, have no longer risen sharply from the previous high base.
However, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased clearly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the probed hypermarkets exceeded 91 forints, at least, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value in the basket stood at 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
The prices of Unicum and live fish remained almost at the level of last year, however prices of turkey, nuts and peacock have increased sharply.
In the shops, the price of flour and bread followed the data from the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, only one kilogram bread was found at 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the bottle of two litres of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle recorded included.
It only prevents this year, in terms of daily shopping, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the least expensive.
According to our calculations, Cora has increased the price of its daily basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan have increased them by about 18 and 18 percent, respectively.
By comparing last year's most expensive basket with the least expensive basket of this year, we find a difference of 12 percent while the difference between last year's lowest and most expensive year's is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices increased by an average of 1,206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the increase in VAT rate was already seen in last year's Christmas prices.
This process made trade unclear, hypermarkets could not clearly determine which margin to apply on products as long as they were unable to predict the impact of the price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, it may lose a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the rate of VAT, the increase in prices of the daily Cart has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was greater than 1,720 forints at the value of 2006 while the difference between the least expensive baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive as the value of the most expensive basket was greater than 1,630 forints last year and the lowest price increased by 1,284 forints as well.
By approaching the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic rise in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer goods increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
