However, according to our information, the number of businesses is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to poll companies not even to reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, were recorded in hospitals.
The sanitary conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the over-handling of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also make the economy on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the hospital's traumatology service János.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria were detected on a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year, a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injury of a serious car accident came out of the hospital but soon after he had to return because of an MRSA infection and since then the doctors have not been able to do a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Up to 10 December of this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, Karolina Böröcz, chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
It is the number of infections caused by a multidrug agent that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we do not have any information.
About two thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e., methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsilitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily cureable.
However, if antibiotics are used in an excessive or inappropriate way, the bacteria, which respond well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant antibiotic bacteria that will rapidly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacteria may cause serious hospital infections, such as trauma infection or septicaemia, on the elderly, of small weight or with a weakened organism.
According to the hospital director János, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the hospital daily.
Above all, the infection with the epidemic should not be confused, we do not find MRSA only the disease or are not looking for it, said Tibor Nyulasi.
S.A.S. withstands antibiotics.
“These sick people are isolated, the caring staff wear rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics suitable for treating them,” Tibor Nyulasi said.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carrying MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not in mode
The vast majority of MRSA infections could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multi-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
The National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most of the cases occur only on the day if MRSA is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has strong recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the management of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts should be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The achievement of microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina Böröcz reported.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that ARMs proliferate from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, to put gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are also detected in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferated by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while, in the end of the epidemic, the sick should be removed from each other by a minimum of 1.5 metres.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save money on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the sick are many, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are observed, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable manner or the proliferation of the pathogens may be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant spending on social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) highlights among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multi-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not in a state of drunkenness
The official finding concerning the fatal accident caused by the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement was drawn up.
It may be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, who resigned from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian by causing his death last Tuesday, would have led in a state of drunkenness or storm, communicated Friday Attila Morvai, spokesperson of the Public Ministry of the capital after the relative finding was established.
