A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million archival documents, which were stored over 27 km of linear in Bad Arolsen, Hesse, were only accessible so far for a \"humanitarian\" purpose, i.e. individual and nominative, upon request of an old victim or his/her legal guardians.
The 11 States in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratifying this agreement by all States has been completed, and the opening of the agreement has been in effect since yesterday.
Sensitive information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow us to carry out research \"in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the state of health of forced workers,\" says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, objected to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subject to compulsory work and, if possible, to provide proof of their internment, in order to open the way for their compensation.
Still in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees deal with tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
\"There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,\" said Fr Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the University Technische Universität in Berlin in 2006.
