Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like the Earth than we thought so far: the European space probe - Venus Express - has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind turbines at the poles, similar to those appearing in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lights on Venus.
The European probe - Venus Express - has now proved this - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lights on Venus explode at a height of about 56 kilometres of cloud in the cloud, reports Christopher Russell from the University of California in Los Angeles in the scientific magazine -Nature -
According to the famous cyprine theory, lightning would have revealed life on Earth: the orage would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, an angle stone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: \"If life has been there, it must have been at a very old date in history,\" says Sean Solomon of the \"Carnegie Institution\" in Washington.
There should not be a lot of living things on the surface of Venus today: the atmosphere is about 100 times denser than on Earth, sometimes there are temperatures of 500 degrees.
\"Venus is perhaps the infernal twin of the Earth, but she remains a twin,\" Russel said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like the Earth in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of \"Venus Express\" in November 2005 was an important step in the Venetian research, since no probe was on the way to explore this planet since the ninety-seven years.
According to researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of \"Nature\" do not just highlight the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than the first ones assumed.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the wind turbines already known at the north pole, a whirlpool of clouds at the south pole, which is much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the currents of air in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Institute of Astrophysica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet qualified as a star of night or morning revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much slower on itself: a Venetian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, does not recall the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has been fixed on Earth in the form of carbonate, it is on Venus most of the atmosphere.
